      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">For Tuberculosis of spine, best diagnostic modality is:</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q6758177",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 392,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        15
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Ans. C) MRI</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option C)</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><ul style=\"list-style-type:disc;\"><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">MRI is the gold standard for diagnosing tuberculosis of the spine.&nbsp;</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">It provides detailed images of both bone and soft tissue structures, which are crucial in identifying vertebral destruction, abscess formation, and spinal cord involvement.&nbsp;</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">MRI is highly sensitive and helps in assessing the extent of the disease and planning treatment, making it the best diagnostic tool.</span></p></li></ul><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Explanation:</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option A. Clinical:&nbsp;</strong>While clinical signs and symptoms (e.g., back pain, neurological deficits, fever) are important for suspicion, they are not definitive for diagnosing spinal tuberculosis. Clinical assessment is often the first step, but it needs to be followed by imaging and microbiological testing for confirmation.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option B. X-ray.&nbsp;</strong>It is the <strong>first investigation</strong> to be done in case of suspected patients. In the early stage of disease, x-rays are usually normal. X-ray can show signs of bone involvement, such as vertebral collapse, narrowing of intervertebral discs, or paraspinal abscesses. However, it is not sensitive enough to detect early disease or to assess soft tissue involvement (e.g., abscesses). X-rays are still commonly used in the initial workup but are less specific compared to MRI.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option D. CT-guided biopsy:&nbsp;</strong>While a biopsy may be needed to confirm the diagnosis through microbiological analysis (e.g., PCR, culture for Mycobacterium tuberculosis), it is not the first-line diagnostic modality. Biopsy is typically performed when there is uncertainty after imaging or when other diagnostic tests are inconclusive.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Educational Objective:</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><ul style=\"list-style-type:disc;\"><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">MRI is the most sensitive and specific diagnostic modality for tuberculosis of the spine, as it can evaluate both bone and soft tissue involvement and is crucial in early detection and treatment planning.&nbsp;</span></p></li></ul>",
