        },
        {
          "id": 1451,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Bone resorption</span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:16px;\">Sunray appearance in osteosarcoma is due to:&nbsp;</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q4881691",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 388,
      "difficulty_level": "beginner",
      "subjects_id": [
        15
      ],
      "solution": "<p><span style=\"font-size:16px;\"><strong>Ans. A) Periosteal reaction</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:16px;\"><strong>Option A)</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><ul style=\"list-style-type:disc;\"><li><span style=\"font-size:16px;\">The \"<strong>sunray</strong>\" or \"<strong>sunburst</strong>\" appearance in <strong>osteosarcoma&nbsp;</strong>is a classic radiological finding. It is due to <strong>periosteal reaction</strong>.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:16px;\">In aggressive bone tumors like osteosarcoma, the tumor grows rapidly and lifts the periosteum.&nbsp;</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:16px;\">In response, the periosteum lays down new bone perpendicular to the cortex, along the Sharpey's fibers that connect the periosteum to the bone.&nbsp;</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:16px;\">Whenever a disease/pathology destroys the bone, cambium layer is irritated and responds by periosteal reaction i.e., bone formation under the periosteum.&nbsp;</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:16px;\">This rapid, perpendicular bone formation creates the characteristic spicules that radiate outwards, resembling sunrays.</span></li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/image_8DRWlnG.png\" width=\"609\" height=\"367\"></p><p>&nbsp;</p><ul style=\"list-style-type:disc;\"><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Thus, periosteal reaction is an indicator that the disease is destroying the bone.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Codman Triangle</strong>: Triangular bony growth seen at angle of lifting of periosteum. It can be seen in any malignant lesion but usually osteosarcoma.</span></li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><img src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/image_HQwyiTZ.png\" width=\"534\" height=\"476\"></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Other Options</u>:</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option B. Muscle fiber calcification:</strong> While calcification can occur in soft tissues with tumors, it is not what gives the specific \"sunray\" appearance which is a bone phenomenon.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option C. Blood vessel calcification:</strong> Calcification of blood vessels (e.g., atherosclerosis) is a separate process and does not typically present as a \"sunray\" pattern in the bone.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option D. Bone resorption:</strong> Bone resorption is the breakdown of bone, which would lead to lytic areas, not the formation of radiating new bone.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Educational Objective</u>:</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><ul style=\"list-style-type:disc;\"><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">The sun-ray appearance seen in the osteosarcoma is due to the periosteal reaction causing calcification along the <strong>Sharpey’s fibers</strong>, giving it a spiculated appearance.&nbsp;</span></li></ul>",
      "correct_choice_id": 1448,
