        15
      ],
      "solution": "<p><span style=\"font-size:16px;\"><strong>Ans. C) MRI</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:16px;\"><strong>Option C)</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><ul><li><span style=\"font-size:16px;\">This case refers to post-traumatic pain in proximal femur.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:16px;\">History of a slip, pain in the right hip, tenderness in Scarpa's triangle, and a normal X-ray strongly suggests a <strong>stress fracture</strong> or an <strong>occult (hidden) fracture</strong>, particularly in the hip or femoral neck, which may <strong>not be visible on initial plain radiographs</strong>.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:16px;\">For stress or occult fracture of neck femur where traumatic marrow edema is seen, <strong>MRI is investigation of choice.&nbsp;</strong></span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:16px;\">It can <strong>visualize bone marrow edema</strong>, which is an early sign of a stress fracture or a hidden trabecular fracture even when plain X-rays are normal.&nbsp;</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:16px;\">MRI is the gold standard for evaluating hip pain when X-rays are normal. It provides excellent detail of:</span><ul><li><span style=\"font-size:16px;\"><strong>Soft tissues:</strong> Muscles, tendons (strains, tears), ligaments, labrum (labral tears)</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:16px;\"><strong>Cartilage:</strong> Early degenerative changes, tears</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:16px;\"><strong>Bone marrow:</strong> Edema (indicating contusions, stress reactions/fractures, early avascular necrosis, or occult fractures not visible on X-ray)</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:16px;\"><strong>Bursae:</strong> Bursitis</span></li></ul></li><li><span style=\"font-size:16px;\">The history of a \"slip in the bathroom\" and pain/tenderness in Scarpa's triangle (femoral triangle, which houses structures like hip flexor tendons, nerves, and vessels, and is near the hip joint capsule) with a normal X-ray strongly suggests a soft tissue injury (e.g., muscle strain, hip flexor tendinopathy, labral tear) or a subtle bony injury (e.g., stress fracture of the femoral neck, early avascular necrosis). MRI is the most sensitive and specific test to diagnose these conditions.</span></li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:16px;\"><strong><u>Explanation</u>:</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:16px;\"><strong>Option A. USG-guided aspiration:&nbsp;</strong>Usually required in cases of <strong>infective</strong> and <strong>inflammatory</strong> synovitis. It helps for diagnostic tap for confirmation of diagnosis.<strong>&nbsp; </strong>While a hip effusion might be present, it won't diagnose an occult fracture. It is not the primary next step for suspected fracture with a normal X-ray.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:16px;\"><strong>Option B. CT scan:&nbsp;</strong>CT scan<strong>&nbsp;</strong>findings are similar to plain radiography, including sclerosis, new bone formation, periosteal reaction, and fracture lines in long bones. CT may be useful in <strong>differentiating stress fractures from a bone tumor or osteomyelitis</strong> if the plain radiographs are negative and bone scans are positive. It is not as sensitive as MRI for early stress fractures or bone bruises. It also involves radiation.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:16px;\"><strong>Option D. Bone scan:&nbsp;</strong>A bone scan is very sensitive for detecting increased bone turnover, which occurs stress fractures. It can show \"hot spots\" where metabolic activity is high. However, it is less specific than MRI, and it often takes 24-72 hours for a stress fracture to become positive on a bone scan. MRI provides more anatomical detail and is often preferred in acute settings for suspected hip fractures due to its higher specificity and ability to rule out other soft tissue injuries.<strong>&nbsp;</strong>Stress fracture that's difficult to detect on an MRI scan, such as the ribs, may recommend a bone scan.&nbsp;</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:16px;\"><strong><u>Educational Objective</u>:</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><ul style=\"list-style-type:disc;\"><li><span style=\"font-size:16px;\">Any <strong>occult fracture&nbsp;</strong>e.g. <strong>Fracture neck femur,&nbsp;</strong>is not visualized on X-ray, so, MRI is investigation of choice.&nbsp;</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:16px;\">For any fracture with marrow edema, example <strong>stress fracture, MRI&nbsp;</strong>is investigation of choice.&nbsp;</span></li></ul>",
