      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">What is the earliest bony change of osteomyelitis on X-rays?</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q2858207",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 393,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        15
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Ans. B)</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Periosteal reaction</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option B)</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><ul><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Pyogenic osteomyelitis on X-ray in 24-48 hours will show loss of soft tissue planes (earliest soft tissue change on X-ray).<strong>.</strong></span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Day 7 to 10: solid periosteal reaction (earliest bony change on X-ray).</strong></span></p></li></ul><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Explanation:</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option A. Loss of soft tissue planes.&nbsp; </strong>This is <strong>earliest x-ray finding</strong> on x-ray (soft tissue) for osteomyelitis.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option C. Sequestrum.&nbsp; </strong>A fragment of <strong>dead infected bone</strong> becomes separated from viable bone&nbsp;and is known as a <strong>sequestrum</strong>. These are late findings of chronic osteomyelitis on radiology.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option D. Lytic defects.&nbsp; </strong>Lytic lesions are&nbsp;areas where bone has been destroyed, leaving a hole in the bone. These lesions in the <strong>spine</strong> are common, and when severe, can lead to one or more vertebral compression fractures, which can be painful and even disabling.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Educational objective:</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><ul><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Periosteal reaction is the earliest bony change seen on the x-ray in case of osteomyelitis, after 7-10 days.</span></p></li></ul>",
